ze, a solid mid-80s horse on his turf form who was last seen at Glorious Goodwood, is an interesting running too in the colours of Qatar Racing.</p><p>In such a competitive event, it is a slight surprise to see Hawkeyethenoo, the top weight, clear favourite at a best price of 3-1, with the rest priced up at 6-1 or bigger. Jim Goldie's eight-year-old has acquitted himself well on his two starts at Lingfield this winter but without suggesting he has such an obvious chance as the market suggests off a 1lb higher mark than last time out, when he was beaten one-and-a-half lengths into second place in a similarly competitive heat.</p><p><strong>George Guru (3.05)</strong>, an 8-1 chance this morning, could be the one to beat him. He has been running well without winning so far this winter, but has mostly been running at a mile when his very best form is over a well-run seven furlongs. He was beaten two necks at Kempton in November off today's mark, with Tarooq – who went on to beat Hawkeyethenoo next time out – back in fifth. Adam Kirby, who has a 20% strike-rate at Lingfield since the start of November, is a positive jockey booking too.</p><p><strong>Aureolin Gulf (6.30)</strong> is in a much lower grade at Wolverhampton but still looks a decent bet at 9-2 to back up solid recent form with a win, while <strong>Seven Woods (2.55)</strong>, who returns to hurdling after a spell over fences, is worth chancing in the Pertemps qualifier at Huntingdon.</p><h2>In other news...<br /></h2><p><strong>Alan King</strong> has his first runner since New Year's Day, having closed his Wiltshire yard to combat a virus that was inflaming the lungs of most of his horses. The noises emanating from the yard have become more positive in the past week, so let's hope all is well; it's a miserable thing to happen to anyone and King took a long time to get over a similar issue five years ago.</p><p>His runner today is <strong>Secret Edge</strong> in Huntingdon's 4pm race but he's begging us not to judge the health of his yard on the sole basis of how this one runs. He's out today because he's entered in a sale next week.</p><p>King will have other runners at Doncaster and Cheltenham tomorrow and they will give us more of an insight.</p><h2>Tipping competition, day five<br /></h2><p>Our winners so far:</p><p><strong>Monday</strong></p><p>Mappin Time 11-4</p><p>Imjin River 3-1</p><p>Reggie Bond 2-1</p><p><strong>Tuesday</strong></p><p>Wood Yer 10-1</p><p>Catching On 11-2</p><p>Kayf Moss 6-1</p><p><strong>Wednesday</strong></p><p>Persian Herald 8-1</p><p>Ubaltique 4-1</p><p>Cloudy Joker 5-2</p><p><strong>Thursday</strong></p><p>Time To Think 2-1</p><p>Full Ov Beans 11-2</p><p>Straits Of Messina 15-8</p><p>And our leader is:</p><p><strong>CorvusFrugilegus</strong> +18.75</p><p>. . . who found his sixth winner of the week in Time To Think. <strong>72luca</strong> (+13.50) moved into second place by pairing that one with Full Ov Beans.</p><p>For today's thrilling climax, we'd like your selections, please, for these races: <strong>2.45 Doncaster</strong>, <strong>2.55 Huntingdon</strong>, <strong>3.50 Doncaster</strong>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>GET THOSE TIPS IN EARLY! In the event of a tie at the end of the week, the winner will be the tipster who, from among those tied on the highest score, posted their tips earliest on the final day (TODAY).</p><p>This week's prize is a copy of <strong>Modern Greats</strong>, the new Timeform publication in celebration of some of the high-achievers who have graced the track in recent years. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2013/dec/18/frankel-timeform-modern-greats-book\" title=\"Guardian\">Our Greg Wood reviewed it here</a> If you don't win, <a href=\"http://www.timeform.com/display_articles.asp?page=Modern_Greats.asp\" title=\"Timeform\">you can buy a copy here</a>.</p><p>As ever, our champion will be the tipster who returns the best profit to notional level stakes of £1 at starting price on our nominated races, of 