ur professional regions and the Welsh Rugby Union. The 28-year-old's decision bucks the recent trend of top players quitting the Welsh domestic game, coming less than 24 hours after Toulon, the reigning European champions, announced <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jan/23/leigh-halfpenny-wales-join-toulon-cardiff-blues\" title=\"\">a lucrative contract for the Wales full-back Leigh Halfpenny</a>.</p><p>Several of Jones's Wales team-mates, including Mike Phillips, Jamie Roberts, Dan Lydiate and James Hook, already play in France, while Halfpenny, the centre Jonathan Davies and the lock Ian Evans will join the exodus later this year. But Jones, a mainstay of the Wales team who captained the British &amp; Irish Lions in their Test series-clinching victory over Australia in Sydney last summer, is staying put.</p><p>\"I am very happy to be able to resolve my future, which means I can now concentrate solely on my rugby,\" he said. \"It's flattering to have received offers from elsewhere, but at this point in my career my focus is on being in the right environment to ensure the longevity of both my domestic and international career.</p><p>\"It's important to me that I am playing the right level of rugby to ensure I am at my best, which is why it makes sense for me to accept the offer on the table from the Ospreys.\"</p><p>Jones, who has 74 Wales caps, is favourite to captain the side in next week's Six Nations opener against Italy if Sam Warburton does not return from a shoulder injury. Jones made his Ospreys debut in 2005, he is their current captain and he was a key figure on the past two Lions tours, featuring in all six Test matches against South Africa and Australia.</p><p>The Ospreys' operations manager, Andy Lloyd, added: \"It will give everybody involved with the region – players, coaches, staff, commercial partners and supporters – a huge boost.</p><p>\"Alun Wyn has been, and continues to be, a fantastic servant to this region and is a true role model to those around him.</p><p>\"A natural leader, he demands the highest standards of himself and everybody in this environment, and it will be a better place with him around in the coming seasons.</p><p>\"Given the uncertainty that still surrounds the game in Wales in general, we've given Alun Wyn reassurances regarding his future options, but it is fantastic news that he is staying at the Liberty Stadium.\"</p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jan/23/leigh-halfpenny-wales-join-toulon-cardiff-blues\" title=\"\">Halfpenny's exit from Cardiff Blues,</a> which will take effect at the end of this season, was accompanied by powerful remarks from the Blues chief executive, Richard Holland, that vividly reflect Welsh rugby's current toxic political climate. Critical areas such as revenue and competition structure remain unresolved amid uncertainty surrounding next season's Heineken Cup. Holland is due to attend a media briefing alongside Blues chairman Peter Thomas on Friday in the wake of Halfpenny's departure.</p>","headline":"Alun Wyn Jones signs new Ospreys deal in boost for Welsh club rugby","trailText":"The Wales lock Alun Wyn Jones has said that 'being in the right environment' was a key factor in him deciding not to move abroad","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3m68q","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2014/1/24/1390559586861/Alun-Wyn-Jones-004.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2014/1/24/1390559586861/Alun-Wyn-Jones-004.jpg","wordcount":"517","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"427919461","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8600875","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Press Association","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-24T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2031965","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-27T10:34:06Z"},"rights":{