n-Jones-010.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Huw Evans/Rex","photographer":"Huw Evans/Rex","altText":"Alun-Wyn Jones","height":"372","credit":"Huw Evans/Rex/Huw Evans/Rex","caption":"Alun Wyn Jones has agreed a new contract that will keep him at Ospreys until after the 2015 World Cup.  Photograph: Huw Evans/Rex","width":"620"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2014/1/24/1390559592939/Alun-Wyn-Jones-009.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Huw Evans/Rex","photographer":"Huw Evans/Rex","altText":"Alun-Wyn Jones","height":"276","credit":"Huw Evans/Rex/Huw Evans/Rex","caption":"Alun-Wyn Jones has agreed a new contract that will keep him at Ospreys until after the 2015 World Cup.  Photograph: Huw Evans/Rex","width":"460"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-427919657","relation":"thumbnail","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2014/1/24/1390559586861/Alun-Wyn-Jones-004.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Huw Evans/Rex","photographer":"Huw Evans/Rex","altText":"Alun-Wyn Jones","height":"84","credit":"Huw Evans/Rex/Huw Evans/Rex","caption":"Alun Wyn Jones has agreed a new contract that will keep him at Ospreys until after the 2015 World Cup.  Photograph: Huw Evans/Rex","width":"140"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2014/1/24/1390559594183/Alun-Wyn-Jones-010.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Huw Evans/Rex","photographer":"Huw Evans/Rex","altText":"Alun-Wyn Jones","height":"372","credit":"Huw Evans/Rex/Huw Evans/Rex","caption":"Alun Wyn Jones has agreed a new contract that will keep him at Ospreys until after the 2015 World Cup.  Photograph: Huw Evans/Rex","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"The Joy of Six: bad losers | Paul Doyle","webPublicationDate":"2014-01-24T10:00:00Z","sectionName":"Sport","sectionId":"sport","id":"sport/blog/2014/jan/24/joy-of-six-bad-losers-sport","fields":{"standfirst":"From a boxing sit-in to an angry press-conference entrance to end all others, via Arsenal, Drummond, Gaucci and Holst","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-01-24T11:30:46Z","body":"<h2>1) <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mO_Aspbv0fw\" title=\"\">Jung-il Byun</a></h2><p>\"Show me a good loser and I'll show your a loser.\" So said Graeme Souness. Or was it Jack Nicklaus? Or Vince Lombardi? Someone else probably said it before all of those guys and is still raging on a street somewhere, beating up passers-by in dismay at missing out on due recognition. Oh well. Still, at least, Jung-Il Byun might sympathise. He was the South Korean boxer who became a punchline thanks to his refusal to accept defeat in the 1988 Olympic Games in Seoul. After being penalised for headbutting during his bantamweight bout with Bulgaria's Aleksandar Hristov, Byun lost 4-1 on points. He and his coaches were so distraught that they filed an immediate appeal in the time-honoured form of an almighty melee. Members of the home crowd joined in by chucking chairs into the ring. Eventually, the fighting died down but Byun's disappointment did not and he began a one-man sit-in protest in the ring. The session's subsequent bouts had to be cancelled. And when everyone else left the arena and the lights were turned off, Byun was still there, sitting in the ring and stewing in his own fury. He and several Korean officials were later suspended for their strops, while the New Zealand referee was the target of so much public scorn that he decided to fly home.</p><h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VmvBI7X5iKg\" title=\"\">2) Jon Drummond</a></h2><p>The fastest men can be the slowest to simmer down. Jon Drummond proved that in the quarter-finals of the 100m dash at the 2003 world championships in Paris. The American was astonished at being disqualified for a supposed false start, repeatedly insisting \"I did not move!\" as he demanded to be reinstated. He then demonstrated his ability to not move by lying motionless on the track and resisting all pleas to get the hell out of the way. After delaying the race for almost an hour, Drummond eventually got up and stomped away, sobbing uncontrollably. Two hours later his manager informed the press: \"He's still crying. We're making him drink water because he's becoming dehydrated.\"</p><h2>3) Arsenal, often</h2><p>In an era in which José Mourinho has muttered hogwash about Unicef-led conspiracies against Chelsea and Sir Alex Ferguson has tended to accept losses with all the good grace of a pub oaf snubbed in his efforts to chat up the barmaid, Arsenal's players and staff stand out for their attempts to give their defeats a wider significance. According to the Arsenal way of thinking, a defeat for Arsenal is, in fact, a defeat for us all. Arsène Wenger is not just a football manager, he is a moral crusader. Arsenal matches do not merely pit one team against another, they are a clash between Good and Evil. It is not a notion entirely without foundation but it has led to some ridiculous displays of outrage. Thierry Henry could be considered to embody this strange amalgam of class and crassness, the Frenchman's rarefied skill contrasting sharply with his base self-serving righteousness. Consider <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ci7XuOCejHAthe\" title=\"\">the tantrum he aimed at referee Graham Poll after Arsenal lost to Newcastle in 2001</a> or his reaction to being beaten by Barcelona in the 2006 Champions League final, after which he suggested that refereeing inadequacy and Barcelona skulduggery were partly to blame for his team surrendering a one-goal lead. <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p9g40mPUGsE\" title=\"\">\"Next time I'm going to learn how to dive maybe,\"</a> he blathered darkly. But I'm not a woman\". And then there's another of Arsenal's captain, William Gallas and <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7PTUMgpHPn0\" title=\"\">his infamous on-field lamentation at Birmingham City</a> in 2008, when the prospect of dropping points to an uncouth mob led him to sit down and sob like a child denied an ice cream.</p><h2>4) Luciano Gaucci</h2><p>The thing about trying to show off your power is that it often achieves the opposite and instead betrays your pettiness. Take Sheikh Fahad Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, for instance. He was the head of the Kuwaiti Football Federation during the 1982 World Cup and decided to flex his muscle in pitiful fashion as his country were being trounced by France. After Alain Giresse took advantage of loose defending to score for France, the sheikh barged regally on to the pitch and demanded that the goal be ruled out for offside, threatening to order his players to walk off unless his wish was granted. After much confusion and negotiation, France agreed to let their goal be rubbed out, safe in the knowledge that they would get plenty more. Another World Cup controversy led to an even more pathetic demonstration of smallness in 2002. Ahn Jung-Hwan scored the winning golden goal that knocked Italy out of the tournament after a series of bad decisions in the hosts' favour.  As it happened, Ahn was employed by an Italian club at the time. But not for long. Perugia owner Luciano Gaucci promptly terminated the Korean's contract, reportedly storming: \"I have no intention of paying a salary to someone who has ruined Italian football\".</p><h2>5) <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XC28aMWxK9g\" title=\"\">Greg Holst</a></h2><p>Canadian Greg Holst was head coach of several Austrian ice hockey teams, including Villach, whose shootout defeat by Vienna Capitals in 2006 was not well received by Holst. Displeased at the officiating, he launched into a now-legendary post-match rant in which he marvellously fused English and German to claim, amongst other things, that \"es ist ein fuckin' complete skandal\". <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OCFj9lf8IQE\" title=\"\">Giovanni Trapattoni's got nothing on this guy</a>.</p><h2>6) Kevin Borseth</h2><p>Please observe <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hEuOTkTQ8h4\" title=\"\">this textbook entrance to a post-match press conference</a>. As for the rest, it's about offensive rebounds. WHAT ELSE DO YOU WANT TO KNOW?!</p>","headline":"The Joy of Six: bad losers","trailText":"<p><strong>Paul Doyle:</strong> From a boxing sit-in to an angry press-conference entrance to end all others, via Arsenal, Jon Drummond, Luciano Gaucci and Greg Holst</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3m6v7","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2014/1/23/1390500520275/Jon-Drummond-003.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2014/1/23/1390500520275/Jon-Drummond-003.jpg","wordcount":"906","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"427873410","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8598703","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Paul Doyle","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-23T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2031730","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-31T10:00:00Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":true,"subscriptionDatabases":true},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2014/jan/24/joy-of-six-bad-losers-sport","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/sport/blog/2014/jan/24/joy-of-six-bad-losers-sport","tags":[{"id":"sport/series/joyofsix","webTitle":"The Joy of Six","type":"series","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/series/joyofsix","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/sport/series/joyofsix","references":[]},{"id":"sport/blog","webTitle":"Sportblog","type":"blog","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/sport/blog","references":[]},{"id":"sport/sport","webTitle":"Sport","type":"keywo