alse\" Name=\"Dark List Accent 4\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"71\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Shading Accent 4\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"72\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful List Accent 4\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"73\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Grid Accent 4\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"60\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light Shading Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"61\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light List Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"62\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light Grid Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"63\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Shading 1 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"64\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Shading 2 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"65\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 1 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"66\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 2 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"67\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 1 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"68\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 2 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"69\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 3 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"70\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Dark List Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"71\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Shading Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"72\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful List Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"73\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Grid Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"60\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light Shading Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"61\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light List Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"62\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light Grid Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"63\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Shading 1 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"64\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Shading 2 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"65\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 1 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"66\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 2 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"67\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 1 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"68\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 2 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"69\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 3 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"70\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Dark List Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"71\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Shading Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"72\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful List Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"73\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Grid Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"19\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtle Emphasis\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"21\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Intense Emphasis\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"31\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtle Reference\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"32\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Intense Reference\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"33\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Book Title\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"37\" Name=\"Bibliography\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"TOC Heading\"/> </w:LatentStyles> </xml><![endif]--> By all measures, this year’s iteration of Big Bash cricket has been a remarkable success. Crowds are markedly up on last year, but possibly more gratifying for organisers has been its rapid ascent as a blockbuster television hit.</p><p>It’s no coincidence this occurred during the first season Big Bash moved from pay TV to primetime free-to-air, albeit during the non-ratings holiday period. Meanwhile another former pay-TV-only code, A-league football, also made its debut on network airwaves this summer via SBS2.</p><p>The repositioning of both sports and the eagerness with which each administration embraced them provokes a salient question: does sport in Australia still need free-to-air exposure to become mainstream? <p>At first glance, the Big Bash experiment provides an emphatic riposte. </p> <p>Even five years ago there were few willing to suppose a Mickey Mouse competition featuring generic franchises, domestic cricketers (many either unfamiliar to the wider public or past their prime), could be summer’s surprise primetime hit. </p> <p>But Big Bash earned its best ratings over the Christmas holidays, when network television choices are stark. The emphatic turnaround in fortunes for Australia in the Ashes also had a halo effect on viewing numbers. We like cricket. And we like it a lot more when we’re beating England. </p> <p>That Big Bash airs nightly and is (as far as cricket goes) brief and easy to follow also assisted it. </p> <p>The most popular Australian television series last year were nightly reality franchises: The Block, My Kitchen Rules and The Voice. With those off-air, there is a gap to fill. If the Big Bash aired in, say, April or September, it would not work.</p> <p>Either way, Ten proved it could generate numbers of about 1 million viewers nationally a night, something Fox Sports cannot do.</p> <p>It’s at this point that we should acknowledge that without Fox Sports, the Big Bash would not have reached this point. Fox was frequently innovative in its coverage, using player mics, on-field cameras and entertaining on-air talent, several of whom Ten poached.&nbsp;</p> <p>Fox Sports has regularly acted as an incubator and&nbsp;when their telecasts generate large numbers, as the Big Bash did, free-to-air often circles. The potential eyeballs offered remain seductive for sporting administrations. </p> <p>Free-to-air digital channels such as 7mate and One may be an impediment for subscription growth. For instance, a fortnight ago, the American NFL playoffs scored 67,000 viewers on Ten’s One digital channel and 45,000 on Foxtel’s ESPN. </p> <p>Compared with the rest of the world, particularly the US, Australia was slow to embrace pay television. Programmers eventually identified the most likely carrot to attract Austrlians to pay: live sport.</p> <p>By contrast with its equivalents elsewhere, Foxtel is an excellent product. Yet despite retaining rights to every AFL and NRL match, most football and cricket, and a giant swath of US sport, household penetration is not what it could be.</p> <p><a href=\"http://if.com.au/2014/01/21/article/Bright-outlook-for-pay-TV-industry/LQZVJSLKCP.html\">According to</a> <i>IF.com.au</i>, the percentage of households that subscribe vary around the country. It’s 35% in Sydney, 28% in Melbourne and Brisbane, 21% in Adelaide, 18% in Perth and just 14% in Tasmania.</p> <p>For those who pay, the sport networks are a boon; they cover sports often ignored or deemed too niche by network television. For this group, the argument is moot. The product is strong, the pictures are in crisp HD (rare for free-to-air) and coverage can be more fan-friendly.</p> <p>Certainly a subset of diehards will eagerly watch Australia’s ODI squad half-heartedly sweat it out against Bangladesh in Dakar. The same group is willing to rise at 3am to witness Lleyton Hewitt play Uzbekistan in a Davis Cup tie.</p> <p>But to those who do not subscribe, many sports shunned by free-to-air exist in a pay-to-play ghetto. To that group, it’s almost as though these events do not exist. </p> <p>Of course free-to-air viewers and networks have something of a love/hate relationship with each other around sport. Networks are impatient, and overtly driven by ratings. If something is not working, no matter how much the rights cost, they will yank it off air. The subscription model allows viewers some certainty that free-to-air does not&nbsp; </p><p>In the past, free-to-air programmers have demonstrated a willingness to cut sports off, delay telecasts, edit out parts of contests, air them at unflattering pre-dawn timeslots or simply warehouse content so competitors cannot get their hands on them.</p> <p>At the premium end, sports such as cricket and rugby league's State of Origin have never been more important to free-to-air networks – they are DVR and piracy proof. This is significant in the US, where one dominant sporting code (NFL) is a surefire ratings winner. </p> <p>Still, sporting bodies such as the AFL are close to a precipice where the limit of what is economically viable for the networks to pay has almost been reached.</p> <p>Equally, following Nine’s big financial losses from covering the London Olympics, Australian networks were hardly eager to sign again with the IOC. Ten eventually did so, primarily because of its dreadful recent primetime ratings.</p> <p>The Olympics are a classic example of the way subscription television can exploit the limitations of free-to-air. Yes, London was a loss-leader for Nine in that they got to promote their slate of programs to a huge audience, but lately evidence of significant post-event traction has not come to fruition.</p> <p>Foxtel’s immersive coverage in London was impressive. Yet the mainstream din was mostly about what Nine's coverage lacked. Foxtel cannot bid for exclusive rights to the Olympics because of its nemesis, the federal government’s anti-siphoning list. Whether that list shrinks under Tony Abbott's government remains to be seen. </p> <p>Yet just because something airs on free-to-air, it will not necessarily attract viewers. Take the National Basketball League. An NBL game on Ten on 12 January landed just 36,000 viewers nationally. On 20 January the figure was 26,000.</p> <p>As for the A-league, overall SBS2 is a positive, but diehard fans will get a better package (more money spent on it, HD pictures, more games) from Fox. And after starting off strongly, certain SBS2 A-league ratings have been modest. The Newcastle-Melbourne Victory clash on 10 January attracted 67,000 viewers on Fox, while 58,000 tuned in on SBS2. </p> <!--EndFragment--> </p>","headline":"Sport on TV: free-to-air still has its strengths if it picks the best moment","trailText":"Big Bash League success shows that the right sport at the right time still delivers more than pay-TV can offer<br>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3m65n","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/24/1390538921789/9b3