e tree-lined boulevard named in honour of the Daytona International Speedway's founder, Bill France, alongside the roar of engines there was a sense of anticipation at what this first meeting of car classes that have never competed against one another might bring.&nbsp;</p><p>The new series is run by Bill's family, the France dynasty that previously owned Grand-Am and has made such a huge success of Nascar in North America.&nbsp;The&nbsp;stated intent is to try and bring some of that popularity to sportscar racing in North America. To that end the 24 hours hosts a generous field of 67 cars, with Daytona Prototypes (DP) and Daytona GT-spec cars from Grand-Am and Le Mans Prototype 2 (LMP2) and Le Mans GT-spec cars from the ALMS set to be racing at the same time come the green flag on Saturday at 2.30pm ET.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;That the DP cars have the advantage at what is their spiritual home on the banking at Daytona was made clear in qualifying despite recent efforts to close the balance of performance between the two classes, with Gurney's time of 1:38.270, a second and-a-half clear of the closest LMP2, Muscle Milk's Lucas Luhr at 139.629 in eleventh, a car he will share in the race with Alex Brundle. Balance of performance across the classes has been a target for the new series but on this basis further tinkering is to be expected as the season progresses.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;Despite the gap to the ALMS runners, Gurney expected the LMP2 cars to double-stint their tyres and gain and “tighten up” the gap with quicker pitstops, whether it will be enough with the differential as it is seems doubtful. But for the organisers the most important fact was that the new series was underway with a successful first session.&nbsp;</p><p>Bill France's granddaughter, Lesa Kennedy who is the Vice Chairman of Nascar and is on the board of directors of TUSC, said before the weekend that she hoped the merger would move sports car racing “to an amazing new level”.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;“Like any motorsport it will continue to evolve and change to reach the audience its looking for so you will see that continual evolution,” she continued. Thus far, however, she added: “It has succeeded our expectations .&nbsp;Any time you take two different sanctioning bodies and merge them together it's going to take time, it will take a lot of effort and so far we have been pleased at how far everything has advanced.”&nbsp; </p><p>So far, so good, then. On track Britain's Richard Westbrook at the wheel of another Corvette DP for the Spirit of Daytona racing team rounded out the front row and the only woman in the top class, Britain's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jan/18/motorsports\">Katherine Legge</a> took eighth in the DeltaWing prototype. The Starworks Riley DP of Scott Mayer was in third but last year's winner Scott Pruett, who is bidding to overtake Daytona legend Hurley Haywood with his sixth 24 Hour win here, could manage only ninth for Chip Ganassi in his Riley DP.&nbsp;</p><p>Gurney who has never won the Daytona 24 and is set to run only five races in the series but claimed a pole in 2007, said it was “one of our times to shine”.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;“We were pretty diligent all through testing in December, concentrating on full-tank runs, But with low fuel it showed what we had,” he said. “When we pulled the fuel out the time came. We were pretty happy with the car and it was nice to get one in there.”&nbsp;</p><p>“It's the biggest race we do and the one we want to win,” he concluded before the final session of night practice was due to commence.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;The Oreca of Colin Braun headed the PC class; in GT Le Mans, the SRT Viper of Marc Goossens took pole and in GT Daytona Christopher Haase was quickest in the Paul Miller Racing Audi R8.</p>","headline":"Gurney claims first pole in new era of sportscar racing at Daytona 24-hours","trailText":"<b>Motor racing:</b>&nbsp;Alex&nbsp;Gurney fastest&nbsp;in&nbsp;Rolex 24 Hours'&nbsp;first co