um Shading 2 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"65\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 1 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"66\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 2 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"67\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 1 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"68\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 2 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"69\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 3 Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"70\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Dark List Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"71\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Shading Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"72\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful List Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"73\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Grid Accent 5\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"60\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light Shading Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"61\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light List Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"62\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Light Grid Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"63\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Shading 1 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"64\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Shading 2 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"65\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 1 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"66\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 2 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"67\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 1 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"68\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 2 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"69\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 3 Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"70\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Dark List Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"71\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Shading Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"72\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful List Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"73\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Grid Accent 6\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"19\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtle Emphasis\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"21\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Intense Emphasis\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"31\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtle Reference\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"32\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Intense Reference\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"33\" SemiHidden=\"false\" UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Book Title\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"37\" Name=\"Bibliography\"/> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"TOC Heading\"/> </w:LatentStyles> </xml><![endif]--> <!--[if gte mso 10]> <style> /* Style Definitions */ table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-name:\"Table Normal\"; mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0; mso-tstyle-colband-size:0; mso-style-noshow:yes; mso-style-priority:99; mso-style-parent:\"\"; mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt; mso-para-margin-top:0cm; mso-para-margin-right:0cm; mso-para-margin-bottom:10.0pt; mso-para-margin-left:0cm; line-height:115%; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:11.0pt; font-family:Calibri; mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin; mso-ansi-language:EN-US;} </style> <![endif]--> Shane Warne has signed on as Australia’s specialist spin bowling coach for the upcoming World Twenty20, continuing a dramatic 12 months of furniture rearrangement in the national coaching ranks.</p><p>With spin set to be a key factor on the pitches in host country Bangladesh, Warne will work closely with Australia’s spin battalion, which now looks like to include 20-year-old Victorian leg-spinner James Muirhead, selected for Australia’s upcoming T20 fixtures against England.</p><p>“We believe our national teams can really benefit from more specific skill-based coaching as and when it is needed,” said national coach Darren Lehmann of Warne’s appointment. “This will mean that from time to time we will enlist the support of experts in their craft to work with our players and share their experience.</p><p>“We believe spin bowling will be critical to success. There’s no better person than Shane to help guide the spinners we select in that squad. We’re thrilled to have him on board.”</p><p>It’s sound logic that has already reaped rewards for the fast bowlers under the guidance of Craig McDermott, and the addition of Warne as a consultant will lend a familiar, campfire feel to the national coaching setup.</p><p>Warne himself was excited at the prospect of lending a hand to the next generation of Australian spinners and said, “I’m looking forward to helping them with some intense bowling preparation ahead of the world Twenty20, where we’ll specifically work on tactics and mindset.”</p><p>The appointment also adds some intrigue to Australia’s selection plans for the tournament. The chairman of selectors, John Inverarity, has said <a href=\"http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/rookie-spinner-james-muirhead-called-up-for-t20-against-england-20140120-314v5.html\">42-year-old Brad Hogg, a form bowler of the current Big Bash, remains in his calculations</a>. Warne’s presence provides some doubt though, and more likely points to the ascension of Muirhead, for whom Warne could be an invaluable sounding board and tutor. <br></p><p>Like two-Test spinner Michael Beer and discarded batsman Rob Quiney, Muirhead is a product of Warne’s old club side St Kilda.</p><p>All-rounder Glenn Maxwell could provide a further spin option for the Bangladesh tournament, but Hogg, Xavier Doherty and Fawad Ahmed will also press their claims.</p><p>Putting Warne on the payroll shapes as an intriguing prospect for Cricket Australia and no doubt they remain mindful of his outspoken tendencies, particularly on selection and management of the national team. The conflicts with Warne’s media work will be minimal. Cricket Australia chief executive James Sutherland and his marketing team are no strangers to leveraging Warne’s involvement and last year’s ugly Big Bash tussle between Warne and Marlon Samuels showed that even the possibility of bad publicity is of no great concern at Jolimont. <br></p><p>In almost every sense they would view Warne’s presence as a net gain, and they are right.</p><p>Fittingly, it’s almost 12 months to the day since Warne published his idiosyncratic and controversial <a href=\"http://www.shanewarne.com/blog/330/where-is-australian-cricket-at-part-1\">“Warnifesto”</a> series of blueprints for Australian cricket, in which he claimed to be “frustrated on many levels” with the direction of the national team. It’s a document that gets more interesting with time. <br></p><p>In it Warne recommended that his friend Lehmann be appointed in a coaching role, which came to pass sooner than even Warne could have expected, though the current T20 captain George Bailey did not even figure among the squad of 16 players Warne <a href=\"http://www.shanewarne.com/blog/332/where-is-australian-cricket-at-part-2\">earmarked for international T20 duty</a> at that point. He has reportedly moved up in Warne’s estimations since.</p><p>The oft-neglected <a href=\"http://www.shanewarne.com/blog/336/where-is-australian-cricket-at-part-4-the-way-forward-spin-bowling\">fourth instalment</a> is pertinent, relating as it did to Australia’s spin bowling stocks. It&nbsp; pitched T20 cricket as “a hindrance in the development of a young spinner”. Warne may have revised that view since, as well as this nugget: “We should identify our top four spinners and put them on a decent contract and have them play nothing but first-class cricket for 12 months.” <br></p><p>In light of the 2013-14 domestic schedule, some Xbox might have been in order too.</p><p>Warne’s appointment is equally a case of the spinner’s cricket life coming full circle. At 21 he was a precociously talented but ill-disciplined bowling prospect at loggerheads with Australian Cricket Academy coaching staff, but developed rapidly under the tutelage of another former Test spinner, Terry Jenner.</p><p>Jenner’s influence on Warne’s career was profound. On his early days working with ‘TJ’, Warne said his late mentor was “the best thing that happened to me there”.&nbsp; Two decades on, Warne himself looms as the wise oracle and holder of spin secrets, so the cycle continues.</p><p>Warne used a section of his 2001 autobiography to criticise the England coaching set-up for having too many greats sitting in commentary boxes rather than providing guidance to the national team. Now he has a chance to step away from the microphone and muck in himself.</p><p>Warne has always been an outspoken critic of modern coaching practices. His hostile views on the pervasive management-speak culture of John Buchanan’s&nbsp; reign are well documented, but also probably sat as a counterweight to his matey, hands-on coaching relationship with Jenner, who was a kindred spirit. He once said of his late coach: “It helped that Jenner was capable of doing everything that he suggested to me.” <p>His pupils can surely only dream of achieving such symbiosis. </p> <!--EndFragment--> </p>","headline":"Shane Warne's expertise outweighs all else as CA brings him inside the tent","trailText":"Warne's knack of attracting all kinds of publicity will not detract from the unique insight he can offer Twenty20 spinners","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3m63j","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/23/1390518102769/c8606dd1-707d-4836-8bab-5cd7c6a69142-140x84.jpeg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/23/1390518102769/c8606dd1-707d-4836-8bab-5cd7c6a69142-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"1","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"427890734","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"52e191d0e4b00f28d73d311e","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Russell Jackson","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-23T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2031823","productionOffice":"AUS","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-27T10:15:42+11:00"},"rights":{"syndicatable":false,"subscriptionDatabases":false},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2014/jan/24/shane-warne-expertise-outweighs-all-twenty20","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/sport/blog/2014/jan/24/shane-warne-expertise-outweighs-all-twenty20","tags":[{"id":"sport/shane-warne","webTitle":"Shane Warne","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/shane-warne","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/sport/shane-warne","references":[]},{"id":"artanddesign/world-twenty20-20